# [[near]] {{gloss|a time or a place}}; [[close]] {{gloss|to a time or a place}}
#: {{uxi|fr|J'habite tout '''près'''.|translation=I live just '''nearby'''.}}
#: {{uxi|fr|J'habite '''près''' de l'épicerie.|translation=I live '''close''' to the grocery store.}}

{{fr-prep}}

# {{lb|fr|formal|or|legal}} [[attach]]ed to, {{n-g|connects a person or an organisation delegated officially to a setting.}}
#: {{syn|fr|auprès de}}
#: {{uxi|fr|un expert '''près''' les tribunaux|t=an expert witness}}
#: {{uxi|fr|les procureurs '''près''' les tribunaux|t=court-appointed prosecutors}}
#: {{uxi|fr|l'ambassade de France '''près''' le Saint-Siège|t=the French Embassy '''to''' the Holy See}}
#: {{uxi|fr|l'ambassadeur '''près''' le Saint-Siège|t=the ambassador '''to''' the Holy See}}

====Usage notes====
* When used as a preposition (before a noun), {{m|fr|près}} must be immediately followed by {{m|fr|de}} ({{m|fr||près de}}). The rare exceptions belong to a very formal register [[#Preposition|listed above]]. For everyday speech and writing, {{m|fr||près de}} is to be used to mean "near something".
* The adverbial phrases {{m|fr|de près||closely}} and {{m|fr|à peu près||approximately}} can be used without {{m|fr|de}} after them.
* {{m|fr|près}} is only used with the embassies and ambassadors connected to the Vatican, as they are actually located outside, in Rome. All the other embassies and ambassadorial titles use common prepositions {{m|fr|en}}, {{m|fr|à}}, {{m|fr|au}} or {{m|fr|aux}} before host nations' names. (See [[:fr:w:Catégorie:Ambassade de France|Ambassades de France]])

